{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#part-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\b\fs72 \cf6 Part 1: Identifying and validating emotion concept representations}}
\f3\b\fs72 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 This section establishes that Claude Sonnet 4.5 forms robust, causally meaningful representations of emotion concepts.\
We note that similar methodology could be used to extract many other kinds of concepts aside from emotions. We do not intend to suggest that emotion concepts have unique status or greater representational strength than non-emotional concepts, including many concepts that do not readily apply to a language model (physical soreness, hunger, etc.). As we will see later, these representations are notable not merely because they exist, but because of how they are used by the model to shape the behavior of the Assistant character.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#finding"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b\fs40 \cf6 Finding emotion vectors}}
\f1\b\fs40 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 We generated a list of 171 diverse words for emotion concepts, such as \'93happy,\'94 \'93sad,\'94 \'93calm,\'94 or \'93desperate.\'94 The full list is provided in\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#full-list"}}{\fldrslt the Appendix}}.\
To extract vectors corresponding to specific emotion concepts (\'93emotion vectors\'94), we first\'a0prompted Sonnet 4.5 to write short (roughly one paragraph) stories on diverse topics in which a character experiences a specified emotion (100 topics, 12 stories per topic per emotion\'96see the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#dataset-generation"}}{\fldrslt Appendix}}\'a0for details).\'a0This provides labeled text where emotional content is clearly present, and which is explicitly associated with what the model views as being related to the emotion, allowing us to extract emotion-specific activations. We validated that these stories contain the intended emotional content through manual inspection of a random subsample\'a0of ten stories for thirty of the emotions; we provide random samples of stories for selected emotions in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#example-stories"}}{\fldrslt Appendix}}.\
We extracted residual stream activations at each layer, averaging across all token positions within each story, beginning with the 50th token (at which point the emotional content should be apparent). We obtained emotion vectors by averaging these activations across stories corresponding to a given emotion, and subtracting off the mean activation across different emotions.\
We found that the model\'92s activation along these vectors could sometimes be influenced by confounds unrelated to emotion. To mitigate this, we obtained model activations on a set of emotionally neutral transcripts and computed the top principal components of the activations on this dataset (enough to explain 50% of the variance). We then projected out these components from our emotion vectors\'a0
\fs19 \cf9 \strokec9 2\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0
\fs25\fsmilli12720 .\'a0By inspecting activations of the vectors on the original training stories, we found that they generally activated most strongly on the parts of the story related to inferring or expressing the emotion, as opposed to uniformly across all parts of the story ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#example-stories-activations"}}{\fldrslt Appendix}}), indicating that the vectors primarily represent the general emotion concept rather than specific confounds in the training data (though they are likely still afflicted by some dataset confounds). We used these as our emotion vectors for subsequent experiments, up until our exploration of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#other-reps"}}{\fldrslt other kinds of emotion representations}}. In contexts where we compute linear projections of model activations onto these vectors, we sometimes refer to them as \'93emotion probes.\'94\
Except where otherwise noted, we show results using activations and emotion vectors from a particular model layer about two-thirds of the way through the model (In a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#represent"}}{\fldrslt later section}}, we provide evidence that layers around this depth represent, in abstract form, the emotion that influences the model\'92s upcoming sampled tokens).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#expected-contexts"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b\fs40 \cf6 Emotion vectors activate in expected contexts}}
\f1\b\fs40 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 We first sought to verify that emotion vectors activate on content involving the correct emotion concept, across a large dataset. We swept over a dataset of documents (Common Corpus, a subset of datasets from The Pile, LMSYS Chat 1M, and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://huggingface.co/datasets/Isotonic/human_assistant_conversation"}}{\fldrslt Isotonic Human-Assistant Conversation}}), distinct from our stories data, and computed the model\'92s activations on these documents and their projection onto the emotion vectors. Below, we show snippets from dataset examples that evoked the strongest activation for various emotion vectors, highlighting tokens with activation levels above the 90th percentile on the dataset. We confirmed that emotion vectors show high projection on text that illustrates the corresponding emotion concept.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
