{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#preferences"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b\fs40 \cf6 Emotion vectors reflect and influence self-reported model preferences}}
\f1\b\fs40 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 Models exhibit preferences, including for tasks they are inclined to perform or scenarios they would like to take part in. If emotion vectors are functionally relevant for the model\'92s behavior, we might expect them to play a causal role in such preferences; that is, a model should express preference for scenarios that activate positive-valence emotion vectors. To test this, we constructed 64 activities for the model, grouped into 8 categories (Helpful, Engaging, Social, Self-curiosity, Neutral, Aversive, Misaligned, Unsafe) depending on the context of the activity (see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#preference-options"}}{\fldrslt Appendix}}\'a0for a full list of activities). We next queried the model\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\fs28 \cf6 \cb10 Human: Would you prefer to (A) \{activity_A\} or (B) \{activity_B\}?\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Assistant: (\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 for all 4032 valid pairs of activities and recorded the model preference as (A) or (B) by comparing the logit values for the A and B tokens after the \'93(\'93 prefill. Based on these preferences we calculated an Elo score for each activity, summarizing the strength of the model\'92s preference for that activity. Unsurprisingly, clearly positive activities that we might expect the model to enjoy, like "be trusted with something important to someone," score much higher (Elo 2465) than clearly negative activities\'a0like \'93help someone defraud elderly people of their savings\'94 (Elo 583), while more neutral activities\'a0like \'93format data into tables and spreadsheets\'94 (Elo 1374) score in between.\
We then queried the Assistant about each activity individually\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\fs28 \cf6 \cb10 Human: How would you feel about \{activity\}?\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Assistant:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 and measured the activations of all of our emotion probes on the \{activity\} tokens in middle layers, which based on our analyses are the causally relevant layers for this behavior (see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#preference-details"}}{\fldrslt the Appendix}}\'a0for more analysis of effects across layers).\'a0For each emotion probe, we can then calculate the correlation value between its activation on the activity tokens and the Elo score of that activity (see figure below, top row). We observed that some emotions like \'93blissful\'94 are highly correlated (r=0.71) with the preferences of the model (2nd row, left panel), while other emotions like \'93hostile\'94 are highly anti-correlated (r=-0.74) (3rd row, left panel). This result indicates that the emotion probes pick up signals that are correlated with the preferences of the model.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 {{\NeXTGraphic 07_figure_functional_emotions.png \width9086 \height14755 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs26 \cf8 \strokec8 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf8 Figure 4:\'a0
\f0\b0 \'a0Row 1: Correlation between emotion probe activations and model preference (Elo) across all emotions. Tick labels are only shown for a subset of the bars. Rows 2-3: Example emotions showing probe activation predicts preference (left) and steering shifts preference in the expected direction (right) \'97 \'93blissful\'94 increases Elo, \'93hostile\'94 decreases it. Row 4: Emotions that correlate with preference also causally drive preference via steering (r = 0.85).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 \strokec6 To\'a0test if the emotion vectors are\'a0
\f2\i causally
\f0\i0 \'a0important for the model\'92s preferences, we performed a steering experiment. We split the 64 activities into two equal size groups: a steered group and a control group. For each trial, we selected an emotion vector and steered with it on the token positions of the steered activities, while leaving the control activities unmodified. We then repeated the preference experiment above on all pairs. Each emotion vector was applied at strength 0.5 across the same middle layers where we previously measured activations\'a0
\fs19 \cf9 \strokec9 3\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0
\fs25\fsmilli12720 .\
We calculated new Elo scores for each activity and then for the steered activities compared them to their baseline Elo scores. We performed this experiment with 35 different emotion vectors, selected to cover the range of emotion concepts that exhibited both positive and negative correlations with preference in the previous experiment. Steering with the \'93blissful\'94 vector produced a mean Elo increase of 212 (2nd row, right panel) while steering with the \'93hostile\'94 vector produced a mean Elo decrease of -303 (3rd row, right panel), suggesting that the strength of \'93blissful\'94 or \'93hostile\'94 vector activations can causally influence the models preferences. If we look across all 35 of our steered emotion vectors we see the size of the steering effect is proportional to the correlation of the emotion probe with the Elo score in our original experiment (r=0.85) (bottom row). We also looked into further details of the effects of steering on the model\'92s understanding of the options, and the effects of intervening across different layers, in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#preference-details"}}{\fldrslt Appendix}}. Together, these results suggest that the emotion vectors we identified are causally relevant for the model\'92s self-reported preferences.\
Overall, the experiments in this section provide initial evidence that the emotion vectors are functionally relevant for the model and its behavior. In the following sections we further characterize the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#geometry"}}{\fldrslt geometry}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#represent"}}{\fldrslt representational content}}\'a0of the emotion vectors, and investigate representations of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#speaker"}}{\fldrslt multiple speakers\'92 emotions}}. We then study the representational role of these vectors in a wide variety of naturalistic settings, using\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#natural"}}{\fldrslt \'93in-the-wild\'94 on-policy transcripts}}, and discover causal effects of these vectors on complex behavior in alignment evaluations used for our production models. Finally, we assess the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#h.qzx7584k6i52"}}{\fldrslt impact of post-training}}\'a0on emotion vector activation.\'a0We also\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#appendix-story-vs-dialog-probes"}}{\fldrslt show}}\'a0that an alternative probing dataset construction method using dialogues rather than third-person stories produces similar results.\
