{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#part-2"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\b\fs72 \cf6 Part 2: Detailed characterization of emotion concept representations}}
\f3\b\fs72 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 This section explores in more depth the organization and content of model\'92s representations of emotion concepts.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#geometry"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b\fs40 \cf6 The geometry of emotion space}}
\f1\b\fs40 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 Having established that emotion vectors appear to capture meaningful information, we investigated the structure of the space they define. Do emotion vectors cluster in interpretable ways? Are there dominant dimensions that organize the model\'92s representations of emotion concepts?\
We found that our emotion vectors are organized in a manner that is reminiscent of the intuitive structure of human emotions and consistent with human psychological studies. Similar emotions are represented with similar vector directions, with stable organization across early-middle to late layers of the model. The primary axes of variation approximate valence (positive vs. negative emotions) and arousal (high-intensity vs. low intensity), which are often considered the primary dimensions of human emotional space\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [9]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 . We do not regard these findings as particularly surprising; we expect that applying a simple embeddings model to our emotional stories dataset, or even to the emotion words themselves\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [10]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 , might uncover similar\'a0structure. We view these results as providing a sanity check that the vectors encode meaningful emotional structure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa372\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs28 \cf6 CLUSTERING\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 We first examined the pairwise cosine similarities between emotion vectors, shown below. Emotion\'a0concepts that we would expect to be similar show high cosine similarity: fear and anxiety cluster together, as do joy and excitement, and sadness and grief. Emotions with opposite valence (e.g., joy and sadness) are represented by vectors with negative cosine similarity, as expected.\
