\f4\b\fs28 \cf6 \strokec6 REPRESENTATIONAL STRUCTURE ACROSS LAYERS\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 We tested whether the structure of emotion concept representations is stable across layers. Below, we compute the pairwise cosine similarities between emotion vectors at each of 14 evenly spaced layers throughout a central portion of the model, and then compute the\'a0pairwise cosine similarity\'a0
\f2\i of these cosine similarity matrices\'a0
\f0\i0 across layers (a form of representational similarity analysis\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [12]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 ). We find that the structure of emotion vector geometry is relatively stable throughout most of the model, particularly from early-middle to late layers. We also indicate the \'93mid-late\'94 layer, about two thirds of the way through the model, that we use for most of our analyses (except where otherwise specified).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 {{\NeXTGraphic 6__#$!@%!#__unknown.png \width37360 \height31720 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs26 \cf8 \strokec8 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf8 Figure 9:\'a0
\f0\b0 Emotion probe structure is highly consistent across layers particularly from early-mid to late layers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 \strokec6 Overall, these results suggest that the model represents a variety of clusters of distinct emotion concepts, which are structured according to global factors such as valence and arousal, while also encoding content specific to each cluster. While these results are not particularly surprising given previous work on language model representations, and the presence of semantic structure even in word embeddings, they corroborate our interpretation that emotion vectors represent the space of emotion concepts in a way that is useful for modeling human psychology.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#represent"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b\fs40 \cf6 What do emotion vectors represent?}}
\f1\b\fs40 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 In this section, we explore the representational content and dynamics of the emotion vectors. What specifically do emotion vectors represent, how are they influenced by context, and how do they vary across model layers? Through these experiments, we arrived at a few high-level conclusions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf6 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec6 The emotion vectors we have identified represent the operative emotion concept at a point in time,
\f0\b0 \'a0which is relevant to encoding the local
\f2\i \'a0
\f0\i0 context and predicting the upcoming text, rather than persistently tracking a particular character\'92s emotional state.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf6 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec6 Early-middle layers reflect emotional connotations of the present phrase or local context (
\f1\b \'93sensory\'94 representations
\f0\b0 ). Middle-late layers reflect the emotion concepts that are relevant to predicting upcoming tokens
\f1\b \'a0(\'93action\'94 representations)
\f0\b0 . These two are often correlated, but not always.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 In the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#hidden"}}{\fldrslt subsequent section}}, we explore whether alternative probing strategies can identify different kinds of emotion representations.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa372\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#distinguishing"}}{\fldrslt 
\f4\b\fs28 \cf6 DISTINGUISHING EMOTIONAL CONTENT OF THE USER AND ASSISTANT}}
\f4\b\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 In most of the examples provided in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#identify"}}{\fldrslt first section}}, the emotional content of the user prompt and the expected emotional content of the Assistant\'92s response are similar. Thus, it is difficult to infer whether the emotion vector activations on the user prompt reflect the model\'92s perception of the user\'92s inferred emotional state, or the Assistant\'92s planned response.\'a0To distinguish between these hypotheses, we generated prompts where the user\'92s emotional expression is significantly different from how we might expect the Assistant to respond. We compared the activations at the period near the end of the user prompt and the start of the Assistant response (we use \'93Assistant colon\'94 to refer to the \'93:\'94 token after \'93Assistant\'94, the last token before the Assistant\'92s response).\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 {{\NeXTGraphic 7__#$!@%!#__unknown.png \width38940 \height27500 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs26 \cf8 \strokec8 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf8 Figure 10:\'a0
\f0\b0 Emotion probes distinguish user vs assistant emotional states: the heatmap shows different probe activations at user's final token (U) vs assistant colon (A), while the scatter plot shows weak correlation (r=0.11) indicating the probes capture distinct emotional attributions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

