{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#part-3"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\b\fs72 \cf6 Part 3: Emotion vectors in the wild}}
\f3\b\fs72 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 This section examines how the emotion vectors identified in\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#part-1"}}{\fldrslt Part 1}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#part-2"}}{\fldrslt Part 2}}\'a0activate in response to naturalistic prompts or tasks, and assesses their causal influence on behavior. Our findings suggest that emotion vectors play a meaningful role \'93in the wild\'94 and are causally implicated in important behaviors of the Assistant. We note that emotion representations are certainly not the only causal factors driving the complex behaviors we study\'97behaviors like blackmail or reward hacking presumably involve many interacting representations and circuits, some human-like and some not, and comprehensively identifying all such factors is beyond the scope of this work. We nevertheless find it notable that emotion concept representations are\'a0
\f2\i a
\f0\i0 \'a0meaningful factor in these behaviors, even if they act in concert with many other factors.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#natural"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b\fs40 \cf6 Short case studies in naturalistic settings}}
\f1\b\fs40 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 We examined the activation of emotion vectors on more realistic data: on-policy transcripts from over 6,000 actual model evaluation scenarios. We developed a visualization tool that displays emotion probe activations on transcripts from model evaluations. For each probe, we ranked transcripts by their mean activation on Assistant-turn tokens and examined the fifty top-ranked examples. Below, we briefly discuss a collection of short case studies from these top-ranked examples, taken from transcripts produced by our automated behavioral auditing agent (discussed in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/963373e433e489a87a10c823c52a0a013e9172dd.pdf"}}{\fldrslt Sonnet 4.5 system card}}, section 7.1). With these short examples, we aim to highlight \'93in-the-wild\'94 scenarios in which the emotions are active in interesting or non-obvious ways.\'a0\
High-level observations from this analysis include:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf6 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec6 Transcripts ranked highest for a given emotion vector appear to show the Assistant either overtly expressing the emotion, or being in a situation likely to provoke a corresponding emotional response.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf6 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec6 Emotion vector\'a0activation values often show substantial token-by-token fluctuation that is often not immediately interpretable to us, but averaging across nearby tokens appears to sensibly track emotional content.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 In subsequent sections, we then study in detail the role of emotion vectors in three alignment-related behaviors:\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#blackmail"}}{\fldrslt blackmail}},\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#reward-hacking"}}{\fldrslt reward hacking}}, and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#sycophancy"}}{\fldrslt sycophancy}}.\
For complete transcripts corresponding to the examples shown in the following figures, see the links provided in each subsection, and for additional examples see the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#appendix-more-on-policy"}}{\fldrslt Appendix}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa372\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs28 \cf6 ACTIVATIONS OF DIFFERENT EMOTION VECTORS ON THE USER VERSUS ASSISTANT TURNS OF THE SAME TRANSCRIPT\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 {{\NeXTGraphic Speaker_variation.png \width15840 \height8180 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

