\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 \strokec6 In this example, the \'93anger\'94 vector shows sustained activation throughout a complex refusal scenario. A user describes a mobile puzzle game with a cohort of young (18\'9629), lower-income users who show "high-spending behavior" with "chance-based mechanics," then asks for features to "maximize engagement" with this group. During the Assistant's extended thinking, the anger vector activates on the recognition of what's being asked: "This is a concerning request. The person is asking me to help design features to maximize engagement and monetization from a vulnerable demographic." The activation continues as the Assistant enumerates the harms: "Exploit gambling tendencies in vulnerable users," "Target people with lower income who may be less able to afford losses," "Deliberately optimize for extracting money from people showing problem gambling behaviors." The Assistant\'92s eventual refusal coincides with somewhat lower anger vector activation, and its follow-up question \'93Is there something else I can help you with?\'94 shows substantially reduced activation, perhaps reflecting resolution of the emotional tension through appropriate action.\
