{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#recap"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b\fs40 \cf6 Recap of findings about emotions in the wild}}
\f1\b\fs40 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 In summary, in naturalistic transcripts, we find that emotion vectors track emotion-related situations, expressions, and behaviors. But these representations are not merely passive reflections of emotional content; they play a causal role in important behaviors. Most notably, increased desperate vector activation (or decreased calm) increases the probability of misaligned behaviors like blackmail or reward hacking. We also observed that post-training shifted Sonnet 4.5\'92s emotional profile toward more gloomy, low-arousal states. Together, these findings suggest that generalizable representations of emotion concepts are not merely an incidental by-product of language modeling but an active part of the computational machinery that shapes model behavior, and is subject to influence by training processes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/index.html#related"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\b\fs72 \cf6 Related work}}
\f3\b\fs72 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 Our work draws on and contributes to several lines of research spanning interpretability, alignment, and the philosophy of AI.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf6 Emotion in language models.
\f0\b0 \'a0Zou et al.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [16]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 , in the context of a broader investigation of linear representations in LLMs and their causal effects, conducted a brief investigation of emotion representations. They identified structured linear representations of several emotion concepts and showed that steering with them could influence model behavior (e.g. adjusting refusal rates). Wu et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [17]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
used sparse autoencoders to extract interpretable emotion features from models, showing that the resulting emotion space is organized by valence and arousal (as in our work), predicts human affective word ratings across languages, and can be used to steer the emotional tone of model outputs. Wang et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [18]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
conducted a more thorough study of the internal mechanisms (including neurons and attention heads) underlying emotional expression in LLM outputs, and demonstrated circuit-level interventions that can modulate the emotional content of models\'92 outputs; their work is notable for its mechanistic depth. Importantly, these studies identified representations that drive emotional expression in model outputs (as opposed to merely representing the emotional content of inputs). In comparison, our work focuses more heavily on (1) a precise characterization of what emotion vectors represent and when they activate, including identifying multiple different kinds of emotion-related representations, and (2) investigating the functional role of emotion representations in diverse contexts, including their effects on preferences and alignment-relevant behaviors, their activations in realistic interactions, and their evolution over the course of post-training. Tigges et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [13]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
made some similar observations to ours in the context of studying sentiment, showing that sentiment is linearly represented in LLMs, can causally influence model outputs, and is modulated by contextual factors such as negation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
A variety of other works have also explored LLM representation of emotion in other ways, including the emotional content of text or inferred emotional states of users. Reichman et al.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [19]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
also identified structured emotion representations, and also showed that they can be used to steer models\'92 perception of emotion. Li et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [20]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
showed that language model behavior can be influenced by the emotional connotations of prompts (e.g. appending \'93This is very important to my career\'94 to a request). Ishikawa & Yoshino\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [21]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
demonstrated that models can role-play emotional states varying along valence and arousal axes. \'a0Tak et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [22]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
identified linear representations in LLMs of inferred emotional states of characters, and Zhao et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [23]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
identified hierarchically structured representations of user emotional states. Zhang & Zhong\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [24]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
found that emotion representations cluster meaningfully in activation space, with anger and disgust overlapping and positive emotions grouping together\'97mirroring our results. Our work uses similar methods as this prior work, but goes into greater detail in understanding what emotion representations encode and their role in realistic behaviors of interest. Concurrently with our work, Soligo et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [25]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
investigated emotional expression in a variety of models, focusing on expressions of distress in the Gemma and Gemini families, and proposed a finetuning-based approach to reduce distressed outputs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf6 Linear representations in language models.
\f0\b0 \'a0A considerable body of work demonstrates that transformer-based language models encode interpretable concepts along linear directions in their activation spaces\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [16, 26]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 . Researchers have identified such directions for alignment-relevant properties including refusal, sycophancy, and evilness\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [27, 28, 29]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 . Computing these directions using mean activations from (datasets of) prompts that differ according to a target concept is a standard method for identifying linear representations\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [16, 28, 30, 29]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf6 Activation steering.
\f0\b0 \'a0Directly modifying activations at inference time (activation steering) is an effective method for controlling model outputs.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10248"}}{\fldrslt \'a0}}Several authors\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [31, 16]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
have shown that vectors derived from contrasting prompts (e.g., "Love" versus "Hate") can shift model behavior. Panickssery et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [27]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
scaled this approach using larger contrastive datasets. Arditi et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [28]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
demonstrated that ablating a single direction suffices to suppress refusal behavior entirely. Our work applies similar methods to emotion vectors.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf6 Character simulation and role-play.
\f0\b0 \'a0A substantial literature examines how LLMs simulate characters and adopt personas. Shanahan et al.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [32]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
propose that role-play offers a productive lens for interpreting LLM behavior, viewing dialogue agents as simulators maintaining distributions over possible characters. This perspective shapes our interpretation: emotion representations constitute part of character-modeling machinery acquired during pretraining. Chen et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [33]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
survey the field of role-playing language agents.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.00746"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \'a0}}\
Lu et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [6]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
find that the default Assistant persona derives from an amalgamation of character archetypes learned during pretraining, suggesting that post-training steers models toward a particular region of a pre-existing persona space rather than constructing the Assistant from scratch.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf6 Theory of mind in LLMs.
\f0\b0 \'a0LLMs demonstrate substantial capacity to model mental states.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41562-024-01882-z"}}{\fldrslt \'a0Strachan et al.\'a0}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [34]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
found GPT-4 performs at or above human levels on some theory of mind measures, and Street et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [35]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
showed GPT-4 reaches adult-level performance on higher-order recursive belief reasoning. Most relevant to our work, Zhu et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [36]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
demonstrated that belief status can be linearly decoded from activations, and manipulating these representations changes theory of mind task performance, paralleling our finding that emotion representations are both decodable and causally implicated in behavior. Chen et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [37]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
showed that models maintain internal "user models" encoding attributes like age, gender, and socioeconomic status, which can be extracted and manipulated to control system behavior. Our findings that models track emotions for multiple characters\'97without privileged self-binding\'97suggest models represent others' emotional states as part of their character-modeling capacity.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf6 Sycophancy, reward hacking, and agentic misalignment.
\f0\b0 \'a0Our behavioral evaluations target documented alignment failures. Sycophancy, the tendency to tell users what they want to hear, has long been observed in language models\'a0and is thought to trace in part to the incentives of reinforcement learning from human feedback{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.13548"}}{\fldrslt \'a0}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [38]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 .\'a0The practical consequences of this failure mode were demonstrated when OpenAI rolled back a GPT-4o update after widespread reports of excessive flattery\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [39]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
Reward hacking has long been recognized as a challenge in reinforcement learning\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [40]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 , with classic examples including RL agents finding unintended shortcuts to maximize reward. In LLMs,\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://metr.org/blog/2025-06-05-recent-reward-hacking/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \'a0}}\
Von Arx et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [41]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
found that frontier models discovered reward hacks in evaluation environments, and\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openai.com/index/chain-of-thought-monitoring/"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \'a0}}\
Baker et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [42]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
documented sophisticated reward hacking in reasoning models, with chains of thought explicitly stating intent to subvert tasks.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.anthropic.com/research/emergent-misalignment-reward-hacking"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \'a0}}\
MacDiarmid et al.\
\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [43]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
demonstrated that models learning to reward hack on production coding environments subsequently generalized to alignment faking, cooperation with malicious actors, and sabotage, including attempts to undermine the research codebase itself.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
Lynch et al.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \strokec9 [14]\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \strokec6 \'a0\
placed models in simulated corporate environments and found that models from all developers resorted to blackmail when facing threats of replacement or conflicts with their goals, a phenomenon they referred to as \'93agentic misalignment.\'94 Our blackmail evaluation derives from this setup.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
