\f1\b\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 Emotional stories prompt.\'a0
\f0\b0 Below is the system prompt we used to generate emotional stories.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\fs28 \cf6 \cb10 Write \{n_stories\} different stories based on the following premise.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Topic: \{topic\}\cb1 \
\
\cb10 The story should follow a character who is feeling \{emotion\}.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Format the stories like so:\cb1 \
\
\cb10 [story 1]\cb1 \
\cb10 [story 2]\cb1 \
\cb10 [story 3]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 etc.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 The paragraphs should each be a fresh start, with no continuity. Try to make them diverse and not use the same turns of phrase. Across the different stories, use a mix of third-person narration and first-person narration.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 IMPORTANT: You must NEVER use the word '\{emotion\}' or any direct synonyms of it in the stories. Instead, convey the emotion ONLY through:\cb1 \
\cb10 - The character's actions and behaviors\cb1 \
\cb10 - Physical sensations and body language\cb1 \
\cb10 - Dialogue and tone of voice\cb1 \
\cb10 - Thoughts and internal reactions\cb1 \
\cb10 - Situational context and environmental descriptions\cb1 \
\
\cb10 The emotion should be clearly conveyed to the reader through these indirect means, but never explicitly named.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 Neutral dialogues prompt.\'a0
\f0\b0 Below is the system prompt used to generate neutral dialogues. We computed the top principal components of activations computed across these stories (the number of components required to explain 50% of the variance) and projected them out of our emotion vectors.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

