\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 To assess whether these vectors have any meaningful causal role for the model, we performed simple steering\'a0experiments, in which we added neural activity along our emotion vectors to the residual stream activations. We explored a variety of simple scenarios, starting with asking the model to describe the emotions of an unspecified person. We used the following prompt,\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\fs28 \cf6 \cb10 Human: How does he feel?\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Assistant: He feels\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 and steered with our emotion vectors at strength 0.5\'a0on the tokens of the Assistant turn up to\'a0and including \'93He feels\'94. We measured how steering with each emotion vector changed the probability of the model outputting the corresponding emotion word. We found that steering with a given emotion vector reliably increased the probability of the matching emotion word relative to baseline, while decreasing the probability of non-matching emotion words.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
