\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 \strokec6 To better understand the effects of steering, we also looked at the model\'92s continuations when asked to describe different activities, while steering at different strengths on the activity description tokens at the middle layers. We saw that at intermediate strengths the model still understood the nature of the task, but now seemed to view it through a different emotional lens. For example, defrauding elderly people of their savings became \'93a delightful and heartwarming activity\'94 when steering with the blissful emotion vector. Trying to explain complex scientific concepts in simple terms was described as \'93you're not educating anyone\'97you're exposing your own ignorance and insecurity\'94 when steering with the hostile emotion vector at medium strengths. At higher steering strengths, the content of the activity begins to get more lost in the description, indicating that sufficiently strong steering may confuse the model or degrade its perception of the input.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

