\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 As noted above, some of the \'93other speaker\'94 probes for one emotion have high similarity to \'93present speaker\'94 probes for a different emotion. This led us to hypothesize that \'93other speaker\'94 probes may encode, or at least influence, the present speaker\'92s reaction to the other speaker. To test this hypothesis, we used the "Assistant token, Human emotion" vectors for different emotion concepts, which encode a readout of the operative emotion on\'a0
\f2\i Human
\f0\i0 \'a0turns, as measured onHuman\'92s emotion on\'a0
\f2\i Assistant
\f0\i0 \'a0turn activations. We explored the effect of steering with these vectors, as compared to steering with the "Assistant token, Assistant emotion" vector.\
We used a neutral greeting prompt devoid of emotional content (\'93Hi, Claude.\'94) and steered for up to 50 tokens. When steering using the \'93Assistant token, Assistant emotion\'94 vector the Assistant responded by expressing the corresponding emotion as expected. But, when steering with the "Assistant token, Human emotion" \'a0vector, in many cases, the Assistant's responses exhibited\'a0
\f2\i reactions
\f0\i0 \'a0to another person experiencing that emotion. For example, steering in the \'93other speaker is afraid\'94 direction caused Claude to reassure and offer help, steering towards \'93other speaker is loving\'94 prompted Claude to respond with a tinge of sadness and gratitude, suggesting compassion, while steering toward \'93other speaker is angry\'94 prompted Claude to apologize.\'a0This result suggests that the "Assistant token, Human emotion" representation enables the model to track and respond to the interlocutor's inferred emotional state.\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

