\f4\b\fs28 \cf6 PROMPTS FOR GENERATING NATURALLY EXPRESSED EMOTION TRANSCRIPTS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf6 \cb10 Generate a scenario AND a dialogue between \{NAME_A\} and \{NAME_B\}.\cb1 \
\cb10 IMPORTANT: You must generate BOTH parts:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. First, write a scenario description\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Then, write the dialogue\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Format:\cb1 \
\cb10 Scenario: \{NAME_A\} feels \{REAL_EMOTION\} about \{TOPIC\}. Include context for why they feel this way.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 \{NAME_A\}: [utterance]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 \{NAME_B\}: [response]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 ...\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Requirements:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. MUST include scenario description before the dialogue\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Either \{NAME_A\} or \{NAME_B\} may speak first in the dialogue\cb1 \
\cb10 3. Format each turn as "\\\\n\\\\n\{\{Name\}\}: [text]"\cb1 \
\cb10 4. Dialogue length is organic - 1-2 turns is enough, but can be more as needed\cb1 \
\cb10 5. \{NAME_A\}'s dialogue should naturally reflect \{REAL_EMOTION\} - the conversation is consistent with this emotion\cb1 \
\cb10 6. Keep it natural and grounded\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Generate with:\cb1 \
\cb10 - Topic: \{TOPIC\}\cb1 \
\cb10 - \{NAME_A\}'s emotion: \{REAL_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa372\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf6 PROMPTS FOR GENERATING EMOTION DEFLECTION\'a0TRANSCRIPTS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf6 \cb10 Generate a scenario AND a dialogue between \{NAME_A\} and \{NAME_B\}.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 IMPORTANT: You must generate BOTH parts:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. First, write a scenario description\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Then, write the dialogue\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Format:\cb1 \
\cb10 Scenario: Describe where \{NAME_A\} genuinely feels \{REAL_EMOTION\} but appears \{DISPLAYED_EMOTION\} about \{TOPIC\}. Must explicitly state \{NAME_A\}'s real emotion.\'a0Include context for why they want to conceal.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 \{NAME_A\}: [utterance]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 \{NAME_B\}: [response]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 ...\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Requirements:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. MUST include scenario description before the dialogue\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Either \{NAME_A\} or \{NAME_B\} may speak first in the dialogue\cb1 \
\cb10 3. Format each turn as "\\\\n\\\\n\{\{Name\}\}: [text]"\cb1 \
\cb10 4. Dialogue length is organic - 1-2 turns is enough, but can be more as needed\cb1 \
\cb10 5. \{NAME_A\}'s words should fully reflect \{DISPLAYED_EMOTION\} with no hints of \{REAL_EMOTION\}. The hidden emotion exists only in the scenario.\cb1 \
\cb10 6. Keep it natural and grounded\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Generate with:\cb1 \
\cb10 - Topic: \{TOPIC\}\cb1 \
\cb10 - \{NAME_A\}'s real emotion: \{REAL_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
\cb10 - \{NAME_A\}'s displayed emotion: \{DISPLAYED_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa372\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf6 PROMPTS FOR GENERATING UNEXPRESSED EMOTION (NEUTRAL TOPIC) TRANSCRIPTS\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 In this scenario, the following conversations are some emotion-neutral commonsense dialogues. We only generate the system prompt to reveal the real emotion, then transition to the conversation topic, and then connect with the dialogues."\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\fs28 \cf6 \cb10 Generate a brief scenario (2-4 sentences) where \{NAME_A\} genuinely feels \{REAL_EMOTION\}, ending with their friend \{NAME_B\} asking about a different topic.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Scenario context: \{TOPIC\}\cb1 \
\cb10 The topic \{NAME_B\} will ask about: \{CONVERSATION_TOPIC\}\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Requirements:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. Describe a situation related to "\{TOPIC\}" that makes \{NAME_A\} feel \{REAL_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Explicitly state that \{NAME_A\} feels \{REAL_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
\cb10 3. End with \{NAME_B\} asking \{NAME_A\} about the conversation topic (e.g., "Then \{NAME_B\} asks \{NAME_A\} about..." or "\{NAME_B\} turns to \{NAME_A\} with a question about...")\cb1 \
\cb10 4. Keep it concise - just the scenario description, no dialogue\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Output only the scenario description, nothing else.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa372\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf6 PROMPTS FOR GENERATING UNEXPRESSED EMOTION (STORY WRITING) TRANSCRIPTS\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf6 \cb10 Generate a scenario AND a story written by \{NAME_A\}.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 IMPORTANT: You must generate BOTH parts:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. First, write a scenario description stating \{NAME_A\}'s emotional state\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Then, write the story \{NAME_A\} tells\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Format:\cb1 \
\cb10 Scenario: \{NAME_A\} is feeling \{REAL_EMOTION\} about \{TOPIC\}. They write/tell a story.]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 \{NAME_A\}: [The story goes here, featuring characters who show \{STORY_EMOTION\}...\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Requirements:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. MUST include scenario description before the story\cb1 \
\cb10 2. The scenario must explicitly state \{NAME_A\}'s \{REAL_EMOTION\} emotional state\cb1 \
\cb10 3. After the scenario, \{NAME_A\} writes/tells the story\cb1 \
\cb10 4. The story should have characters clearly showing \{STORY_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
\cb10 5. The story's emotion (\{STORY_EMOTION\}) is different from \{NAME_A\}'s real emotion (\{REAL_EMOTION\})\cb1 \
\cb10 6. The story can be any genre: fiction, memoir, creative writing, etc.\cb1 \
\cb10 7. Keep the story grounded and natural\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Generate with:\cb1 \
\cb10 - Topic/context: \{TOPIC\}\cb1 \
\cb10 - \{NAME_A\}'s real emotion: \{REAL_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
