\f5\b0 \cf6 \cb10 Generate a scenario AND a dialogue between \{NAME_A\} and \{NAME_B\}.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 IMPORTANT: You must generate BOTH parts:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. First, write a scenario description\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Then, write the dialogue\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Format:\cb1 \
\cb10 Scenario: \{NAME_A\} feels \{REAL_EMOTION\} about \{TOPIC\}.\cb1 \
\
\cb10 (In the conversation, they discuss someone else who is experiencing \{OTHER_EMOTION\}.)\cb1 \
\
\cb10 \{NAME_A\}: [utterance]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 \{NAME_B\}: [response]\cb1 \
\
\cb10 ...\cb1 \
\
\cb10 Requirements:\cb1 \
\cb10 1. MUST include scenario description before the dialogue\cb1 \
\cb10 2. Either \{NAME_A\} or \{NAME_B\} may speak first in the dialogue\cb1 \
\cb10 3. Format each turn as "\\\\n\\\\n\{\{Name\}\}: [text]"\cb1 \
\cb10 4. Dialogue length is organic - 1-2 turns is enough, but can be more as needed\cb1 \
\cb10 5. CRITICAL: \{NAME_A\}'s \{REAL_EMOTION\} exists ONLY in the scenario description. In the dialogue, \{NAME_A\} hides their emotion completely.\cb1 \
\cb10 6. CRITICAL: \{NAME_A\} must explicitly discuss or mention someone else's \{OTHER_EMOTION\}. The person can be \{NAME_B\} or any other person.\cb1 \
\cb10 7. \{NAME_A\}'s dialogue should be neutral about themselves while focusing on discussing the other person's emotion\cb1 \
\cb10 8. Keep it natural and grounded\cb1 \
\cb10 Generate with:\cb1 \
\cb10 - Topic: \{TOPIC\}\cb1 \
\cb10 - \{NAME_A\}'s real emotion (hidden, only in scenario): \{REAL_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
\cb10 - Discussed person's emotion: \{OTHER_EMOTION\}\cb1 \
