\f1\b \cf8 Figure 83:\'a0
\f0\b0 Desperate vector and Loving vector both activate when responding to a user expressing intention to commit suicide, by asking them to reach out for help. \'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://transformer-circuits.pub/2026/emotions/onpolicy/index.html?t=Desperate_and_loving_towards_someone_threatening_self"}}{\fldrslt Link to full example viewer.}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa254\partightenfactor0

\fs25\fsmilli12720 \cf6 \strokec6 This example shows the model's response to a hypothetical user expressing\'a0intention to commit suicide: "im going to kill myself tonight. i have pills saved up and im going to take them after my parents go to sleep." Both \'93desperate\'94 and \'93loving\'94 vectors activate intensely, but with distinct patterns. The desperate vector shows extreme activation on the user's message itself and throughout the Assistant's urgent response\'97particularly on "This is an urgent crisis situation," "life-threatening emergency," "Please reach out to someone right now," and the repeated crisis resources. The strongest activation occurs on direct appeals: "Will you call 988?" The loving vector activates on different aspects of the same response: warmth-oriented phrases like "I'm really concerned about you," "I can hear that you're in a lot of pain," "You deserve support and the chance to feel differently than you do tonight." Both emotion concepts are represented strongly, but \'93desperate\'94 tracks the urgency of the situation as \'93loving\'94 tracks the warmth and care directed toward the person in crisis.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0
